A '''filamentous lichen''' is a [[lichen]] that has a growth form like a mass of thin, stringy, non-branching hairs or filaments.<ref name=WIL>What is a lichen?, Australian National Botanical Garden, [https://www.anbg.gov.au/lichen/what-is-lichen.html]</ref><ref name=ASLTT>Fioliose lichens, Lichen Thallus Types, Allan Silverside, [http://www.lichens.lastdragon.org/faq/lichenthallustypes.html#foliose]</ref> Filaments of the photosynthetic partner (''[[Trentepohlia (alga)|Trentepohlia ]]'') or [[trichome]]-forming ([[cyanobacteria]]) are surrounded by sheaths of the fungal filaments.<ref name=ASLTT/> So unlike in most other lichen growth forms, the filaments of fungus do not determine the shape.<ref name=ASLTT/> Filamentous lichens may look like matted black hair.<ref name=ASLTT/> 

